column1: NET - 009 - WWT Process Ordering and Configuration
column34:
*This RACI related risk is specifically around WWT processes for Networking Facilities such as the Equinix Performance Hub and specifically around Network Operations / Security Operations:*

1.  If equipment is ordered by WWT on behalf of Infra Ops for replacement or failover, how would Infra Ops teams initiate the process?

2.  When equipment is received, when does ownership change hands from WWT to RTX?

3.  When do vendor support service triggers begin for equipment (RMA, Warranty)?
 * When WWT receives the order for staging prior to racking and stacking / testing?
 * When WWT installs the equipment at the target destination and loads configurations?

4. Which party is responsible for updating the rationalized Network BOM and low-level architecture diagrams?
 * WWT and Network Engineering?
 * Network Operations?
 * BOM and mappings maintained within TEM?
column247: 17/Nov/21 11:59 AM;kjetil.storaker@rtx.com;Confirming with Max Chang whether this can be closed.;;;
column248: 17/Nov/21 12:49 PM;kjetil.storaker@rtx.com;As per conversation with Max on 11/17 the items listed here have been addressed with Equinix. Can be considered resolved. ;;;

column1: NET - 009 - WAN Circuit Orders
column34:
This may cross between Build (Network Engineering and Run (Infra Ops / NOC / NetOps). Today, the Collins Core Network Team straddles Build and Run within Collins Network Services in current-state.

*The risk is detailed around transition-state (pre-Day 1) and future-state (>Day 1) RACI:*
 # *RTX EIS responsibilities:* Which EIS team orders the WAN Circuits, Network Engineering or NetOps / NOC in the transition (pre-Day 1) and future-state (>Day 1)?
 # *RTX EIS PMO:* How should WAN Circuits be ordered, through TEM (future-state) or using an RFP (transition-state)?
 # *RTX EIS Finance / Procurement:* Is such an order a CAPEX investment or CAPEX expense going forward and which Project Optimus and future-state bucket can be used for Network WAN Site Turn-Up activities (remote sites)?
column247: 17/Nov/21 12:00 PM;kjetil.storaker@rtx.com;Confirming with Max Chang if this can be closed.;;;
column248: 17/Nov/21 12:13 PM;kjetil.storaker@rtx.com;This is tracked as risk by 004 - Services, Design, Ordering and Delivery Coordination. Doesn't need to be tracked as a risk for NOC.;;;

column1: AeroCloud current setup and configuration
column34:
The current AeroCloud setup and configuration has some existing issues that are pushing our completion of the EIM inhouse Dev environment out.  They are as follows:

Network is open to all despite assurances that the Palo Alto FW was blocking all traffic and connections had to be whitelisted.

Any additional security groups that are added to the configuration are ineffective as the Ansible configuration re-instates the default groups.

Documentation in confluence does not match the environment.
column247: 08/Jul/21 4:43 PM;Camille.Fremed2@rtx.com;This risk has been mitigated through discussions with Andrew and the cloud team.  Marking this as closed.;;;
column248: 08/Jul/21 4:45 PM;Camille.Fremed2@rtx.com;Mitigated through discussions with Cloud team.;;;

column1: Secrets Management Strategy & Implementation
column34:
The Applications teams require a standardized / approved secrets management solution from Cyber enabling automations for development, deployment, and software integrations in cloud environments.

The lack of standardized solutions will result in application teams executing at risk or the inability to migrate / modernize applications for cloud hosting.

column1: Container Orchestration Strategy & Implementation
column34:
The Applications teams that will be migrating to cloud or modernizing for cloud native require the ability to leverage container and orchestration solutions.  Standard services are needed for Cyber requirements / services to harden, test, and monitor and Cloud to host & execute containers leveraging kubernetes orchestration platforms.

The lack of standardized solutions will result in application teams executing at risk or the inability to migrate / modernize applications for cloud hosting.

 * RTXnet Network Cisco CE/Edge  (Infrastructure)
 * RTXnet Network Cloud Interconnect (Aviatrix) (Infrastructure)
 * RTXnet Network Core Cisco Perf Hub Route/Switch (Infrastructure)
 * RTXnet Out of Band Management (Infrastructure)
 * RTXnet Performance Hub Facilities (Infrastructure)
 * RTXnet Load Balancing (Infrastructure)
 * RTXnet DDI (DNS/NTP/DHCP) (Infrastructure)  - (note VM in AWS Infoblox)
 * RTXnet COE Taps / Packet Brokers (Cyber)
 * RTXnet Email Content Scanning Gateway (Cyber)
 * RTXnet End User Access (AnyConnect) (Cyber)
 * RTXnet Full Packet Capture (Cyber)
 * RTXnet IDS/IPS (Cyber)
 * RTXnet Network Analysis/APT Threat Detection (Cyber)
 * RTXnet Remote Access Gateway - Netscaler (Cyber)
 * RTXnet Security Incident and Event Monitoring ( SIEM )  (Cyber)
 * RTXnet SOCKS Proxy (Cyber)
 * RTXnet Trusted Party Connection (TPC) (Cyber)
 * RTXnet Web App Firewall (WAF) (Cyber) (FUTURE)
 * Zscaler
 * Identity Kit
 * Collins WebVPN (Collins Cyber)
 * Collins Virtualization (Collins Infrastructure)
 * Collins TACACS+  (Collins Cyber)
 * Collins Firewall   (Collins Cyber)
 * RTXNet Infrastructure and Operations Tools (Netscout, VMWare Smart NCM)
 * RTX TACACS

List of technologies in Network and Cyber stacks (sent by Michael Collins):
 * FW - CheckPoint
 * FWIDS - CheckPoint
 * IDS – McAfee/FirePower
 * Fidelis
 * SMTP - IronPort
 * Remote Access – Netscaler/PulseSecure/AnyConnect
 * WAF – F5
 * PCAP
 * NetFlow – Cisco generation (consumption/collection is not in the hub)
 * APIgw – Layer7/Apigee
 * ESXi
 * SIEM Collector/Forwarder
 * WinEventLogs (most likely tied to SIEM and/or syslog)
 * Syslog Collector/Forwarder
 * WebProxy – McAfee/ZScaler/SOCKS
 * VPN/IPSEC – Cisco/Checkpoint
 * Network – Cisco/F5

column1: CyberIdentity - Additional Attributes Needed for SSO (Dependency)(SSO)
column34: Many applications that are being integrated with RTX SSO are dependent upon the completeness and accuracy of the attributes they're consuming (i.e. Workday Employee ID, userPrincipalName, etc). This potentially means user records in data stores that are not fully manged by Identity systems (i.e. EIM non-managed countries) and/or are incomplete will require manual intervention (out of band updates) by data store owners. Remediation: EIM Rest of World (long term) and self-service updates via MyDirectory correlation campaign (short term)

column1: DXC data discovery
column34:
DXC to pull missing fields as described below:

o	[Existing Service Account name (if applicable)]
o	[DHCP ( Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol)]
o	[Special Network / Firewall requirements ]
o	[Internal/External SSL Certificates (if applicable)]
o	[DNS Configuration & Registration -Dynamic/ Static (if applicable)]
o	[Application Service Account Access level]
o	[What is the unique identifier for the user?                                                        ]
o	[Is domain name or domain controller hostname/IP is hardcoded in application?]
o	[Latency requirements (one-way, round trip)/ Data Sharing]
o	[Does the application have a need for MFA (Multi-Factor Authentication)?       ]
o	[Do you require a recurring user feed from the Corporate Directory?]
o	[Storage Type (SAN, NAS, Isilon etc.)]
o	[Clustered (Y/N)]
o	[Cluster Configured (Failover Cluster/NLB Cluster, SQL Cluster, Hyper-V Cluster)]
o	[ATO Required (Y/N)]
o	[Load Balancing Configuration ]
column247: 29/Jun/21 2:28 PM;kevin.barry@rtx.com;To be added to App Factory ;;;

column1: Cyber Identity - SSO Application Onboarding Rescope (SSO)
column34: Application deployment will be re-scoped to include only those applications that consume data fields that are currently enabled within Ping and available in legacy data stores (user directories). Applications that require data attributes which must be provided via RTX SSO Framework 2.0 (RTX LDAP/VDS integration) will not be targeted for integration with Ping until after Aug 1, 2021.

column1: Selection of NextGen FW vendor

column1: VMware ESXi security hardening guidelines
column34:
Cyber typically waits for DISA to release there corresponding STIG, then build the RTX hardening guide from that source document.

 The STIG for v7 has not been released yet, my suggestion would be to utilize the v6.5 guide and flex where it makes sense.

Need to identify what feature/story it should link to with Cybersecurity....
column247:
15/Jun/21 2:08 PM;edgar.deboue@rtx.com;From Tavis Gillard:  We typically wait for DISA to release there corresponding STIG, then build the RTX hardening guide from that source document.
The STIG for v7 has not been released yet, my suggestion would be to utilize the v6.5 guide and flex where it makes sense. 

From Scotty Cranfill:  We plan on designing for vSphere 7 and can utilize the VMware Security Guidelines.
https://blogs.vmware.com/vsphere/2020/10/announcing-the-vsphere-security-configuration-guide-7.html

From Kevin Toolsie:  We do have hardening guidelines that were leveraged on the hRTN side of the house, but they are version specific and may be dated. Do you know what major version would be considered for deployment? 
I expect that following the NIST and CMMC guidelines would be an excellent starting point, but RTX will reserve the right to alter the design to suit the organization and our compliance regimes as needed.;;;

column1: Leverage Bluecat for ADX Migration Opens Vulnerability with Kerberos
column34:
The path forward to Azure for the ADX environment will be to include the WAN, Firewall and DNS teams review the current implementation at the Chicago and Dallas hubs where hUTC connects to hRC (and behind that connection is how B/E Aerospace and IMS connect thru the hRC network).

 

Risk is documented to determine if it’s an acceptable risk until the nextgen Infoblox platform is in place.

 
 * Seeking to leverage Bluecat for ADX Migration Testing –  Since Infoblox won’t exist for 18 months.
 * Testing can be performed with Bluecat. Unfortunately, there won’t get Kerberos authentication from the client, which opens up a vulnerability.
 * We are documenting a risk to move forward with the risk and mitigation to the risk 
 * With Bluecat able to forward DNS resolution; FWs will need to be opened and be able to route.  Risk will need to be accepted.
column247: 06/Jul/21 3:28 PM;Cheryl.Bell@rtx.com;Due to the delays in Infoblox and Networking we have opened this risks.;;;

column1: Hardware Procurement (Microchip shortage)
column34:
Hardware Suppliers have informed us to expect delays in procuring new equipment due to shortage of chips.

6/25/2021 - Equinix PO to be cut/ Acuative SOW to be finalized/ Cable BOM PO sow to be finalized

 6/14/2021 - The shortage is still in affect. A few of the remaining BOMs are being finalized and POs are being cut.

6/7/21 - Demos is receiving new hardware timelines that should improve the majority of the hardware from Cisco. 
 6/1/21 - Equipment expected to arrive in September. Working on bring date into July. 
 5/11/21 - Expected to have an update 5/12.
column247:
01/Jul/21 6:03 PM;max.chang@rtx.com;Can this Project Optimus level program risk be broken out by the Network design teams which own the affected BOMs (Network WAN/MAN Transformation, Equinix Facilities, Security Operations Engineering...)? The current semiconductor chip shortage is exceptionally broad-based and disproportionally affects many older generations of Networking devices with lower manufacturing rates due to their legacy lithography/fabrication/finishing processes; making it difficult for both suppliers and their customers to track progress against specific asset classes much less an entire product family. 

The only way the Project Optimus PMO can report up the downstream impact and timeline risks related to each of these workstreams is if a BOM / supply chain-related procurement request is highlighted as critical path to a Network Design Team's milestones. Currently, this risk is largely un-addressable as resources and capacity cannot be applied against it to alleviate, mitigate, or resolve the issue. 

Our current Jira solution for representing these Network risks is through converting stories into features and by applying parent epics that may span multiple design iterations. This solution is not sustainable nor does this accurately represent the risk at hand making it better to split out this broad risk into addressable chunks. The following is preferred as an example. 

 

*If there's a product family / class of Cisco enclosure, class of Cisco dedicated power supplies, Out-of-Band management devices, specific product class of managed Cisco routers, or class of appliances provided by other Networking suppliers critical to managing the network that is determined to be affected by the microchip shortage with the following conditions**:*
 # Aligned to a particular Network Design team's submitted BOM.
 # Will cause that Network BOM to be incomplete for the duration of an iteration.
 # Is expected to be used to augment or build-out our 6 CONUS + 1 INTL Equinix Performance Hubs by EOY 2021 and/or tied to the Circuit RFP.
 # Must be certified by RTX Network Engineering Team's Staging & Testing process prior deploying at an Equinix Performance Hub, certified by the IRAMP team for utilization in production, and/or augmented for full ATO approval.
 # And is critical path to Network Service Delivery (e.g. initiating WWT's support engagement on rack mounting, cabling, and staging / functionally testing configurations associated to those affected devices).

*Then this detailed risk can be addressed by the Equinix Facilities team by:*
 * Working with WWT and the equipment vendor to exclude these devices for initial staging and load testing if all teams mutually agree that this will not impact testing or certification accuracy.
 * WWT and service delivery teams can provide timely feedback on implications of excluding these devices for Staging & Testing and formalizing this exception by documenting them as exceptions for IRAMP/ATO.
 * The larger team may mutually decide that equipment Staging & Testing cannot be accomplished with accuracy without these critical components and prioritize other non-critical path tasks associated to WWT or the equipment Vendor + the IRAMP/ATO team. 
 ** The downstream timeline expectations related to delivering the 6 CONUS / 1 INTL Equinix Performance Hub augmentations and builds may be modified and continuously updated and communicated to reflect this new reality.
 * When the Network equipment eventually becomes available, the IRAMP certifications /ATO approvals may resume and equipment gradually incorporated to be accurately load tested and to resolve noted exception requests for any IRAMP exceptions and/or outstanding ATOs.

In this example case, even if the detailed risk is determined to directly impact a Network design team's delivery dates and *determined to be immediately un-addressable* (by ES Strategic Partnerships/Sourcing /Procurement, IRAMP/ATO, Network Transformation WAN/MAN, Equinix Performance Hub Facilities, and by WWT due to a known global supply chain issue) the potential positive outcomes (choose to refine a process or work on other non-critical path items related to WWT's or another partner's service delivery) are still valuable and would benefit the Equinix Facilities team's ability to deliver regardless of when the equipment supply may become available. Otherwise, WWT engagement, ongoing IRAMP/ATO, and resources applied toward system maintenance may be stalled entirely while other parallel activities may have still been accomplished without issue.

 ;;;

17/Jun/21 8:28 PM;max.chang@rtx.com;*ES Tool Scope:*

The scope of this risk is related to DevOps monitoring capabilities supported by the EIS DevOps Cloud Operations tool stack.

*Current-State Asset CI Scope / Data Governance Model:*
 EIS DevOps Cloud Operations team maintains a DevOps monitoring stack for Microsoft Active Directory Infrastructure and multi-cloud Server Monitoring and Alerting to support Cloud VMs provisioned across AWS EC2 and Azure. There is a working metadata tagging structure in place for DevOps Cloud provisioned assets and FedRAMP certification for ingestion, enrichment, and storage of application logs to support DevOps development using this established data governance structure.

*Transition & Future-State Asset CI Scope / Project Optimus Support:*
 RTX Network WAN/MAN/LAN device assets are not supported within the RTX DevOps data governance model and should be maintained separately in order to optimize and scale tool support for re-hosted applications + cloud VMs driven by the EAS App Factory workstream which has infrastructure nodes that fall within the Application Architecture.;;;

column1: Governance (GRC) intake process for COTS IaaS/PaaS hosted tools and SaaS services
column34:
Complete an agreed upon GRC intake process for all Infrastructure Ops tools and applications that do not have underlying infrastructure currently managed (Infrastructure may be owned or leased with a 3rd party managing platform Build and Run) by RTX Operations and Support.

This intake process may include an Application Risk Questionnaire for the RTX Product Owner that identifies the Application Architecture and Network Peering Model and for the 3rd parties that manage the tool, Supplier Risk Questionnaire detailing system components and Cyber Risk Questionnaire that certifies their vulnerability management processes are vetted. The 3rd party workflows are approved by the Cyber Compliance team in lieu of running RTX vulnerability scans on Infrastructure assets that are not hosted in a RTX managed DC, within an RTX Managed Private Cloud, and/or hosted in Commercial Clouds outside of RTX control.

column1: Governance (GRC) intake process for RTX Managed tools and applications
column34:
Complete the approved intake process for any RTX hosted and managed tools and applications with underlying RTX owned Infrastructure assets (either owned outright and/or leased by RTX). These are Applications (COTS) and Application Services that have underlying infrastructure and BCP managed directly by RTX EIS Operations and Support services. The application infrastructure may be hosted in an RTX Data Center, a RTX Colo managed by a 3rd party provider, or in an RTX Commercial Cloud environment.

Tools / Applications that are RTX Managed should have an Application CI record certified and maintained within an RTX approved CMDB. There must be enough baseline configuration data related to underlying Server Infrastructure assets and ITSM Assignment Group data within either the Application CI record or its parent Business Service for RTX Operational Support to manage and own the Change Management, Incident Management, Problem Management, and Major Incident Management (if criticality is recorded as Mission Critical by the RTX Service Owner) processes throughout the application production lifecycle.

column1: NET-007-Future Hardware Maintenance Support
column34: The RTN DXC agreement ends in June 2022 and DXC provides the hardware maintenance as part of a bundled charge referred to as an RU (Revenue Unit) associated with WAN Routers.  A decision needs to be made as to who will provide maintenance, and what the funding source is, for hRTN sites after the current RTN DXC contract end date.  Without maintenance as part of the support model, network issues could cause financial and scheduling issues for the business.
column247: 14/Jun/21 3:25 PM;andy.chan@rtx.com;End date target for 10/1/2021.;;;

23/Jun/21 9:45 AM;max.chang@rtx.com;What we've learned is that there are certain dates where transition must occur from a service provider perspective and a technology management perspective. The latter has been typically scheduled to be later than the former so RTX has some breathing room to decide on the right path forward.

More to come.;;;
